Rating: 3
Here are some adjustments for eliminating wheat and dairy, and for using a fresh apple, which I had on hand, istead of dried. I also reduced the sugar and fat, and it's STILL a great recipe. It came out really yummy! (I just made it a 2nd time.) Instead of wheat flour, use whole spelt flour. (Or mix spelt and garbanzo or brown rice flour. I used 1 c. spelt, 1/2 c. rice flour.) Skip the sour cream, and use 1/2 c. unsweetened applesauce and 1/8 c. soymilk. For the apple, I threw a cored med-lg apple in the food processor with skin, and pulsed it for very course chopping. I reduced the brown sugar to 5/8 c. (1/2 plus 1/8 c.), and the walnuts to 1/2 c. Great out of the oven, but tasted even better the 2nd day.

Rating: 4
These are great muffins. I doubled the recipe and used 2 cups of fresh chopped apples. I used 1 cup vanilla yogurt (instead of the 2 cups of sour cream I should have used for doubling) and with the fresh apples, it was plenty moist. I only had 1 cup brown sugar, so I used 1/2 cup white sugar in addition, and it was plenty sweet. I also sprinkled cinnamon sugar on top before baking for a sweet top. Made 12 big muffins and 12 mini muffins.

Rating: 4
fluffy, yummy muffins! per previous reviewers, i made the following modifications: * instead of 1 c. sour cream, i used 1/3 c. sour cream + 1/3 c. yogurt * instead of dried apples, nuts, raisins, i used 2 small fresh apples chopped * instead of 1 c. brown sugar, i used 3/4 c. * i sprinkled the tops with cinnamon + sugar before putting into the oven * i only used the mixer to beat the eggs and sugar. after that, i mixed by hand. maybe that's why my muffins came out fluffy and not dense. my yield was 12 muffins too.

